    <div class="section-head page-head">
      <span class="section-tag">Help</span>
      <h1>Frequently asked questions</h1>
      <p class="lede">Connecting a device, what the health number means, and how WhatBattery reads your battery.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-list">
      <div class="faq-item" id="wifi">
        <h3>How do I connect an iPhone or iPad over Wi-Fi?</h3>
        <p>A device shows up automatically once macOS can reach it. The setup is a one-time thing:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Trust the Mac once over a cable.</strong> Connect the device with a cable, unlock it, and tap <em>Trust</em> (enter the passcode). The first pairing can't be done wirelessly.</li>
          <li><strong>Turn on Wi-Fi sync.</strong> In Finder, select the device in the sidebar, open the <em>General</em> tab, tick <em>"Show this iPhone when on Wi-Fi"</em>, then click <em>Apply</em>.</li>
          <li><strong>Same network, awake.</strong> Keep the Mac and the device on the same Wi-Fi network with the device awake, then unplug. It appears in WhatBattery's iPhone / iPad tab.</li>
        </ol>
        <p>Not showing up? Make sure Finder &rsaquo; Settings &rsaquo; Sidebar has "CDs, DVDs and iOS Devices" ticked, try a different cable or port, and confirm you tapped Trust. Wi-Fi discovery can be slow; reconnecting the cable briefly wakes the link.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item" id="genuine">
        <h3>Can WhatBattery tell if my battery is genuine?</h3>
        <p>Not reliably, so it doesn't claim to. macOS only flags a non-genuine battery through a system process, and there's no public signal to check a genuine battery against, so any "genuine / fake" badge would be a guess. Instead WhatBattery shows the battery <strong>condition</strong> (below), which is the trustworthy "is my battery OK or does it need service" answer.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item" id="health">
        <h3>Why does WhatBattery's health differ from other battery apps?</h3>
        <p>WhatBattery computes health the same way <strong>Apple's own Settings</strong> does, from the nominal charge capacity. Some tools read a slightly different capacity field and land a couple of points lower. Neither is wrong; WhatBattery matches the number you see elsewhere in macOS.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item" id="condition">
        <h3>What do the battery conditions mean?</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Normal</strong>: healthy, no action needed.</li>
          <li><strong>Service Recommended</strong>: worn but working; plan a replacement.</li>
          <li><strong>Service Battery</strong>: a fault macOS flags for service.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>This is read from macOS, so it matches what System Settings reports.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item" id="safe">
        <h3>Is it safe? Does it change how my Mac charges?</h3>
        <p>WhatBattery is strictly read-only. It reads battery and power data through Apple's own interfaces and never writes to the battery or changes charging behaviour.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item" id="charging">
        <h3>How does the charger verdict work?</h3>
        <p>When you charge your Mac, <a href="/#pro">Pro</a> records the session and compares what the charger actually delivered against what your Mac is rated to fast-charge at, for example <em>"58W of 96W"</em>. A charger that falls clearly short gets flagged as underpowered, the slow-charger warning macOS never gives you. It only judges a real charge that started from a low battery, where your Mac genuinely pulls full power, so a quick top-up from a nearly full battery is never wrongly called weak. Each session also records how fast the charge ran, how hot the battery got, and any thermal throttling.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item" id="accessories">
        <h3>What about my keyboard, mouse, and AirPods?</h3>
        <p>WhatBattery shows the live battery level of connected Bluetooth accessories, a keyboard, mouse, trackpad, or AirPods, in the dropdown and the Accessories tab. AirPods are broken out per bud and case. Many third-party devices don't report a level over Bluetooth, so those show <em>"Battery unavailable"</em>. Showing the levels is free; <a href="/#pro">Pro</a> adds a per-device history, a time-till-empty estimate, a low-battery alert, and the option to show an accessory's level in the menu bar.</p>
        <p>macOS asks for <strong>Bluetooth access</strong> the first time you open the Accessories tab. It's used only to read these levels locally, nothing is sent anywhere, and the rest of the app works fine if you decline.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item" id="requirements">
        <h3>What does it need?</h3>
        <p>An Apple Silicon Mac running macOS 14 or later. Reading an iPhone or iPad uses the same connection Finder uses; no app is needed on the device. Reading Bluetooth accessory levels needs Bluetooth access, which macOS prompts for when you open the Accessories tab.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
